moral character.

08:20.927 --> 08:23.803
Uh, everybody's doing it.

08:23.838 --> 08:26.631
-I realize that, but--
-But you went public, margie.

08:26.666 --> 08:27.825
We can take it to court,

08:27.860 --> 08:30.068
But i wouldn't expect
to be successful.

08:30.103 --> 08:32.986
Oh, we--We have to try.

08:33.022 --> 08:35.410
I have geared my whole life
toward going to harvard.

08:35.446 --> 08:36.672
I just...

08:38.376 --> 08:40.792
i need to try.

08:42.062 --> 08:43.431
Please.

08:44.779 --> 08:46.016
I don't know, jerry.

08:46.051 --> 08:47.736
You say she didn't have
a prescription.

08:47.771 --> 08:48.976
All the kids
are doing this, alan--

08:49.011 --> 08:50.434
Geing it
without prescriptions.

08:50.469 --> 08:52.206
Well, that's not much
of an argument.

08:52.241 --> 08:55.166
You could argue that rescinding
her admission is arbitrary

08:55.201 --> 08:57.945
Since they have
no official policy.

08:58.382 --> 09:01.204
Oh, alan.
Um, hey, jerry.

09:01.239 --> 09:03.795
Alan, there's a drug--

09:03.830 --> 09:06.066
It's called, uh, dimebolin,
something like that--

09:06.101 --> 09:08.842
And i want it.
My doctor won't give it to me.

09:08.877 --> 09:11.036
It's from russia.
It stems off alzheimer's.

09:11.071 --> 09:12.876
Denny, slow down.
I can't at the moment.

09:12.911 --> 09:14.030
I've taken
a little too much adderall.

09:14.065 --> 09:15.119
Adderall?

09:15.154 --> 09:17.373
See? That's what margie takes,
that and ritalin.

09:17.408 --> 09:18.454
Ritalin. I love ritalin.

09:18.489 --> 09:21.276
Denny, what did we agree on
regarding your medicines?

09:21.311 --> 09:22.891
I would be in charge.

09:22.926 --> 09:25.023
Yeah, yeah, yeah, but i'm
the one with the alzheimer's.

09:25.058 --> 09:28.007
I'll take what i want,
and right now, i want dimebolin.

09:28.042 --> 09:30.098
And you've gotta
help me get it.

09:41.256 --> 09:42.840
You okay, jerry?

09:44.171 --> 09:45.573
Academic doping...

09:45.608 --> 09:47.671
it has such a stigma to it.

09:48.067 --> 09:51.414
What about emotional doping?

09:51.449 --> 09:52.857
What do you mean?

09:54.269 --> 09:56.529
That's what i do--
Emotional doping.

09:56.564 --> 09:59.185
I take
my little helpers to...

10:00.452 --> 10:02.599
do you think
it reflects poorly

10:02.634 --> 10:04.294
On my moral character?

10:04.295 --> 10:04.991
No.

10:05.026 --> 10:06.565
What's the difference?

10:06.600 --> 10:09.005
Well, your medication
is prescribed for one thing.

10:09.040 --> 10:09.682
Mostly.

10:09.717 --> 10:13.697
And second, you have a specific,
diagnosed condition, jerry--

10:13.732 --> 10:14.945
Asperger's syndrome.

10:14.980 --> 10:17.865
Three years ago, you couldn't
even make eye contact.

10:17.900 --> 10:19.720
I take pills
that affect my brain

10:19.755 --> 10:21.786
To help me perform better.

10:21.821 --> 10:24.115
Jerry,
i'm the first one to say

10:24.150 --> 10:25.922
We have
an overmedicated society.

10:25.957 --> 10:28.339
We've got 3 year olds
on antipsychotics.

10:28.374 --> 10:31.179
People who don't even have
high cholesterol take statins.

10:31.214 --> 10:33.654
People take sleep aids
when maybe they should just

10:33.689 --> 10:35.215
Read a book or masturbate.

10:35.250 --> 10:36.398
I-It's out of control.

10:36.433 --> 10:39.975
But that's not to say that many
drugs don't do a lot of good.

10:40.010 --> 10:41.415
They save lives.

10:41.450 --> 10:45.389
People need drugs like insulin
or blood pressure medicine

10:45.424 --> 10:46.936
To simply
maintain their health.

10:46.971 --> 10:51.959
And drugs help some people
to live normal, productive lives

10:51.994 --> 10:53.703
Who might otherwise not.

10:53.738 --> 10:56.397
You fall into that category.

10:56.432 --> 10:58.546
Popping pills to...

10:58.698 --> 11:00.131
Get better s.A.T. Scores--

11:00.166 --> 11:04.372
That's...
something different.

11:37.286 --> 11:39.458
You are not working here,
catherine.

11:39.493 --> 11:41.057
That much has been decided.

11:41.092 --> 11:44.136
Well, then what are
we doing in your office,

11:44.171 --> 11:45.840
Behind closed doors...

11:45.875 --> 11:48.815
where you could
sexually ravage me

11:48.850 --> 11:51.342
With no witnesses
to say it didn't happen?

11:52.085 --> 11:54.784
We're here because i'm told
you're a friend of alan's.

11:55.122 --> 11:57.438
And as a courtesy to him
and you,

11:57.473 --> 11:58.778
I thought
i would at least give you

11:58.813 --> 12:03.321
An opportunity to explain
why you're doing this.

12:04.276 --> 12:06.622
I'm doing it because i'm old

12:06.657 --> 12:09.030
And i'm bored.

12:09.750 --> 12:12.439
All my friends are dead.

12:12.474 --> 12:14.487
It's not like
i could go skiing

12:14.522 --> 12:17.067
Or--Or mountain climbing or...

12:17.422 --> 12:22.232
honestly, a-Assuming i were
qualified to be your assistant,

12:22.267 --> 12:25.891
Uh, would you
employ somebody my age?

12:26.857 --> 12:27.934
Probably not.

12:27.969 --> 12:30.028
I didn't think so.

12:32.100 --> 12:33.730
I got that on tape, dear.

12:33.765 --> 12:36.720
Now i can e you
for age discrimination.

12:36.755 --> 12:40.458
Best you keep me on,
avoid the controversy.

12:40.969 --> 12:42.841
Get out, catherine.

12:54.959 --> 12:57.150
I didn't cheat.
I took medicine

12:57.185 --> 12:59.301
To help my brain function
at its highest level.

12:59.336 --> 13:02.232
You didn't have a prescription
for the medication.

13:02.267 --> 13:05.007
A dozen faculty members
at cambridge university

13:05.042 --> 13:07.095
Admit to taking
unprescribed adderall

13:07.130 --> 13:09.230
To improve their own
academic performance,

13:09.265 --> 13:11.410
But nobody's expelling them.

13:11.445 --> 13:14.068
They're claiming it shows
poor moral character.

13:14.103 --> 13:15.009
And i reject that.

13:15.044 --> 13:18.615
Helicopter pilots take prescription
stimulants to stay alert.

13:18.650 --> 13:20.906
Medical interns take
drugs for narcolepsy

13:20.941 --> 13:21.948
So that they can work all night.

13:21.983 --> 13:23.699
Should we indict
all of them as well?

13:23.734 --> 13:26.299
All they've done is use
a pharmacological tool

13:26.334 --> 13:28.951
So that they could do
their work more effectively.

13:29.328 --> 13:30.395
Certainly you're aware

13:30.430 --> 13:32.659
That harvard has
extremely high standards.

13:32.694 --> 13:33.402
Of course.

13:33.437 --> 13:34.820
John f. Kennedy was a graduate.

13:34.855 --> 13:36.186
As was the unabomber.

13:36.221 --> 13:38.585
-F.D.R.
-Hitler's foreign press secretary.

13:38.620 --> 13:40.401
Numerous literary figures--

13:40.436 --> 13:41.455
Emerson, thoreau--

13:41.490 --> 13:43.024
And the cardinal archbishop

13:43.059 --> 13:45.290
Who shielded child molesters
from prosecution.

13:45.325 --> 13:46.036
For faculty,

13:46.071 --> 13:48.471
You had timothy leary
and his l.S.D. Experiments--

13:48.506 --> 13:51.677
Ms. Coggins, do you want
to go to harvard or not?

13:53.324 --> 13:54.732
Yeah, i do...

13:56.587 --> 13:57.870
desperately.

13:57.905 --> 14:01.725
My point is...
harvard's not perfect,

14:01.760 --> 14:03.352
But neither am i.

14:03.926 --> 14:05.401
But at every opportunity,

14:05.436 --> 14:09.251
I endeavor to be the best
possible version of myself.

14:10.110 --> 14:12.981
And that's all i was doing
by taking ritalin.

14:21.144 --> 14:22.891
The early trials
have been encouraging.

14:22.926 --> 14:24.892
It's in
the stage 3 trials now.

14:24.927 --> 14:25.704
I want it.

14:25.739 --> 14:27.672
Well, you can't have it.

14:27.707 --> 14:28.323
Why not?

14:28.358 --> 14:29.882
Because it's not
f.D.A. Approved.

14:29.917 --> 14:31.425
-This drug is a long way--
-I don't care.

14:31.460 --> 14:35.313
Mr. Crane, i'm not allowed
to prescribe this medication.

14:35.348 --> 14:37.499
And even if i were and did,
you still couldn't get it

14:37.534 --> 14:38.528
-Since it hasn't been--
-How long before

14:38.563 --> 14:41.067
It's available to the public?

14:41.471 --> 14:43.846
My guess is at least two years,
probably three.

14:43.881 --> 14:45.832
-The f.D.A. Hasn't even analyzed
-I-I'll--I'll be dead

14:45.867 --> 14:47.440
-The data of the trials--
-In three years.

14:47.475 --> 14:48.567
Where's the drug?
Who's got it?

14:48.602 --> 14:50.428
Well, pfizer just bought
the rights,

14:50.463 --> 14:53.673
But nobody can just say,
"okay, i'll give it to you."

14:53.708 --> 14:55.160
It would be illegal to do so

14:55.195 --> 14:57.344
Unless you get yourself
enrolled in a clinical trial,

14:57.379 --> 14:59.060
But i think it's fully booked.

15:02.534 --> 15:03.484
Let's be fair.

15:03.489 --> 15:06.914
It's not just the s.A.T.
That gets a person admitted.

15:06.949 --> 15:07.757
Of course not.

15:07.792 --> 15:10.744
Margie, in fact, is also
a national merit finalist,

15:10.779 --> 15:13.999
Captain of her swim team,
class valedictorian.

15:14.034 --> 15:15.229
We get applications

15:15.264 --> 15:17.478
From thousands
of national merit finalists,

15:17.513 --> 15:20.564
Thousands of captains
and thousands of valedictorians.

15:20.599 --> 15:21.948
But this one,
you offered admission.

15:21.983 --> 15:25.476
Yes, until she admitted she had
used brain enhancent drugs.

15:25.511 --> 15:28.027
As do thousands
of other students.

15:28.062 --> 15:29.486
Do you have a way
to weed all of them

15:29.521 --> 15:30.574
Out of your applicant pool?

15:31.141 --> 15:31.901
No.

15:31.936 --> 15:34.684
And there's actually
no policy at harvard

15:34.719 --> 15:38.219
Explicitly forbidding
what you term "academic doping,"

15:38.254 --> 15:39.907
-Is there?
-I think in future--

15:39.942 --> 15:42.611
So you intend to enforce
future rules against her.

15:42.646 --> 15:44.420
Do you think that's fair?

15:44.550 --> 15:46.893
We consider her actions
to be immoral,

15:46.928 --> 15:47.927
And we reserve our right

15:47.962 --> 15:50.411
To make our admissions decisions
accordingly.

15:56.598 --> 15:59.637
I've decided not to sue you.

15:59.672 --> 16:00.661
How sweet.

16:01.163 --> 16:02.172
Listen,

16:02.207 --> 16:05.143
Th-That part about me being desperate
for a distraction,

16:05.178 --> 16:06.671
That was true.

16:06.706 --> 16:08.662
It isn't fair, carl.

16:08.697 --> 16:10.156
I have my health

16:10.191 --> 16:13.505
A-And my mind
is as sharp as--As...

16:14.786 --> 16:17.177
well, you people come up
with all this medicine

16:17.212 --> 16:19.905
To--To--To keep us alive,

16:19.940 --> 16:20.920
Even thrive,

16:20.955 --> 16:22.993
And you don't know
what to do with us.

16:23.028 --> 16:27.337
I was thinking...
if i were to come up

16:27.372 --> 16:29.679
With something
i could sue for,

16:29.714 --> 16:30.817
Something legitimate,

16:30.852 --> 16:32.837
And it could
make the firm money--

16:35.155 --> 16:36.370
Uh... i suppose

16:36.405 --> 16:40.081
If you had
a legitimate cause of action,

16:40.116 --> 16:41.349
Then we would--

16:43.184 --> 16:44.552
Drugs.

16:44.587 --> 16:46.786
Uh, okay, they make them
too expensive,

16:46.821 --> 16:48.650
-While in canada, you can--
-No.

16:49.779 --> 16:50.850
Inflation.

16:50.885 --> 16:53.561
Uh, our social security
payments

16:53.596 --> 16:55.207
-Don't keep pace--
-No.

16:56.778 --> 17:01.521
Oh. Look, some jobs still have
a mandatory retirement age.

17:01.556 --> 17:02.865
No.

17:03.773 --> 17:05.464
These are all legitimate.

17:05.499 --> 17:08.863
Catherine,
you have to have standing.

17:08.897 --> 17:11.962
It has to
directly impact you,

17:11.997 --> 17:14.137
Harm you.

17:15.026 --> 17:16.843
Look how insensitive
you're being.

17:16.877 --> 17:19.017
Th-This is exactly
the problem.

17:19.051 --> 17:21.416
We're just shoved aside
as a nuisance.

17:21.452 --> 17:25.029
I can't even watch
television shows, for god sake,

17:25.064 --> 17:27.996
Because the networks
consider me irrelevant.

17:28.031 --> 17:31.316
You'd think they don't program
for anybody over 50.

17:31.351 --> 17:32.591
Is it any wonder

17:32.626 --> 17:35.482
I'm out knocking over
convenience stores?

17:36.193 --> 17:39.501
You actually
may have something there.

17:39.536 --> 17:40.462
The networks--

17:40.497 --> 17:44.013
They're supposed
to serve the public.

17:46.474 --> 17:48.418
Okay, catherine...

17:48.453 --> 17:50.369
we'll take that case.

17:51.017 --> 17:52.376
Really?

17:52.411 --> 17:54.164
I'm over 50 myself...

17:54.771 --> 17:57.966
and i want something to watch.

18:08.038 --> 18:09.107
How we doing?

18:09.142 --> 18:10.642
Fine.

18:14.573 --> 18:16.865
I got a hearing
before judge peyton tomorrow.

18:16.900 --> 18:18.596
We'll take our best shot.

18:21.830 --> 18:25.007
Shirley's at the fat farm.
You hear?

18:25.042 --> 18:27.062
Why? She's not fat.

18:27.097 --> 18:27.888
You know brides.

18:27.893 --> 18:32.302
They like to get all skinny
before the wedding.

18:32.337 --> 18:35.174
It's all about
how they look in their dress.

18:40.099 --> 18:47.011
You know the best part
of having, uh... mad cow?

18:47.046 --> 18:49.290
Sometimes...

18:49.325 --> 18:50.657
not often...

18:53.112 --> 18:55.360
i think
we're still together.

18:58.263 --> 19:02.462
As delusions go,
it's one of the better ones.

19:11.932 --> 19:14.745
You gonna be okay, denny,
attending her wedding?

19:17.746 --> 19:19.907
Yeah. Well...

19:20.553 --> 19:22.275
what i'm not okay with is...

19:22.310 --> 19:24.445
sitting on my ass
while my brain rots.

19:24.480 --> 19:26.728
I have a big problem
with that, though.

19:28.624 --> 19:31.235
We go before judge peyton
in the morning.

19:33.750 --> 19:36.493
Yeah, you told me.

19:48.255 --> 19:49.963
You gonna stay here
all night, jerry?

19:49.998 --> 19:50.758
It's not even clear

19:50.793 --> 19:52.802
Those drugs gave her
all that much of an advantage.

19:52.837 --> 19:55.397
She scored 99th percentile
on the practice test,

19:55.432 --> 19:56.590
Which she took
without the drugs.

19:56.625 --> 19:58.533
Jerry, she cheated.
Let's not kid ourselves.

19:58.568 --> 19:59.607
Most kids
get a bigger advantage

19:59.642 --> 20:00.818
By taking
the s.A.T. Prep program.

20:00.853 --> 20:03.748
They actually can boost scores
by 150 points.

20:03.783 --> 20:05.198
Those programs are legitimate.

20:05.233 --> 20:06.786
And not affordable
to kids like margie.

20:06.821 --> 20:07.704
Let's face it, katie.

20:07.739 --> 20:09.882
The rich have such a leg up
in this college racket.

20:09.917 --> 20:12.029
According to one chancellor,
in ivy league schools,

20:12.064 --> 20:15.804
Poor applicants really only
get a shot at 40% of the slots.

20:15.839 --> 20:18.202
The rest are reserved
for families of privilege.

20:18.337 --> 20:21.565
But jerry, you cannot be
a fan of academic doping.

20:22.321 --> 20:24.705
I'm just saying...

20:24.967 --> 20:27.398
life isn't
an even playing field,

20:27.433 --> 20:31.162
And for those who are...

20:31.197 --> 20:33.068
weaker than...

20:33.794 --> 20:35.171
meaning you?

20:36.092 --> 20:39.766
Jerry, you're not weaker than.
You have asperger's.

20:40.421 --> 20:43.056
You have no idea
how afraid i am

20:43.091 --> 20:45.224
To leave my apartment.

20:45.563 --> 20:47.090
Every day...

20:47.125 --> 20:48.996
every morning,

20:49.031 --> 20:53.462
I actually wonder, will i
get out the door or not?

20:53.497 --> 20:55.926
It seems you win
that battle every day.

20:56.482 --> 21:00.197
Yeah... on drugs.

21:07.438 --> 21:10.298
You can't sue the networks.

21:10.333 --> 21:13.353
The airwaves, judge, are
a public trust, at least as far

21:13.388 --> 21:15.052
As the broadcast networks
are concerned.

21:15.087 --> 21:17.203
-That's why they're regulated.
-It's still a business.

21:17.238 --> 21:19.498
I mean, bungee jumping
might be regulated.

21:19.533 --> 21:20.624
Are you saying
that those outfits

21:20.659 --> 21:22.224
Would have a duty
to service the elderly?

21:22.259 --> 21:24.162
No, that would be unreasonable.

21:24.197 --> 21:27.436
But to require a broadcaster
to program for everybody isn't.

21:27.471 --> 21:29.214
Mr. Suck.

21:29.249 --> 21:30.166
Sack.

21:30.201 --> 21:31.527
Your honor,
there may have been a time

21:31.562 --> 21:34.234
When it made practical business
sense to exclude the old,

21:34.269 --> 21:34.788
But not today.

21:34.823 --> 21:37.214
Americans over 50 make up
the fastest growing market.

21:37.249 --> 21:38.500
It's about money,
not how many--

21:38.535 --> 21:41.742
Really? Gee. I would've
never guessed that.

21:41.777 --> 21:44.139
The baby boomers,
now all over 50,

21:44.174 --> 21:46.446
Earn $2 trillion
in annual income.

21:46.481 --> 21:47.834
<i>That's trillion.
</i>

21:47.835 --> 21:50.569
Madison avenue is after
the discretionary spender.

21:50.604 --> 21:54.001
Yes, and people over 50
account for half of that, too.

21:54.036 --> 21:56.648
Choose your statistic.
Go ahead. I've got you.

21:56.683 --> 21:59.593
We've got more money.
We spend more money.

21:59.628 --> 22:01.568
We watch more television,
go to more movies.

22:01.603 --> 22:04.280
We buy more cds
than young people do,

22:04.315 --> 22:08.167
And yet we're the focus of less
than 10% of the advertising.

22:08.202 --> 22:10.782
All the networks want to do
is skew younger.

22:10.817 --> 22:12.159
Kid shows for kids.

22:12.194 --> 22:17.033
You know, the only show
unafraid to have its stars over 50 is "b"--

22:18.062 --> 22:20.689
Gee, i can't say it.
It would, um, break the wall.

22:20.724 --> 22:23.057
Oh, mr. Suck.
It's still sack.

22:23.092 --> 22:25.808
I can't tell the networks
what shows to make.

22:25.843 --> 22:28.486
No, but yocan order them
not to discriminate.

22:28.521 --> 22:32.654
What they're doing intentionally
excludes a class of society.

22:32.689 --> 22:33.998
That's bigotry.

22:34.033 --> 22:36.669
You know, we should be able to
turn on our damn televisions

22:36.704 --> 22:37.423
And see something

22:37.458 --> 22:41.059
Other than reality shows
aimed at fourth graders,

22:41.094 --> 22:42.510
Games shows aimed at those

22:42.545 --> 22:44.935
Slightly smarter
than fifth graders

22:44.970 --> 22:46.257
And scripted shows

22:46.292 --> 22:49.394
With dim-Witted,
sex-Crazed 20-Somethings

22:49.429 --> 22:52.156
Running around in suits
or doctor scrubs.

22:52.191 --> 22:53.828
Old people,
the ones with intelligence,

22:53.863 --> 22:56.388
Don't want to watch that crap.
We're fed up!

22:56.423 --> 22:59.562
You know, the networks might
think we're dead, but we're not.

22:59.597 --> 23:02.817
We're very much alive
with working brains.

23:02.852 --> 23:06.591
Give us something to watch,
damn it!

23:13.624 --> 23:14.841
You ready, denny?

23:20.038 --> 23:21.254
Denny?

23:28.834 --> 23:30.098
What's wrong?

23:30.734 --> 23:32.353
I must have nodded off.

23:33.356 --> 23:34.657
I was...

23:36.064 --> 23:38.752
dreaming about shirley.

23:39.636 --> 23:41.535
We were on a bench.

23:41.979 --> 23:44.658
<i>She asked me to marry her.</i>

23:47.116 --> 23:48.779
What a dream.

23:53.412 --> 23:56.544
Were my eyes closed
when you came in?

23:57.756 --> 23:58.723
Yeah.

24:02.063 --> 24:04.287
You must have nodded off.

24:06.341 --> 24:06.879
You ready?

24:06.914 --> 24:08.982
We're due in court.

24:24.123 --> 24:27.615
Mr.Shore, the supreme court
already ruled on this very issue.

24:27.650 --> 24:28.966
No, they didn't, judge.

24:29.001 --> 24:31.373
The supreme court, in fact,
refused to rule on it.

24:31.408 --> 24:33.205
They couldn't be bothered
to even hear the case.

24:33.240 --> 24:35.038
I'm sure if one of
their friends were dying,

24:35.073 --> 24:36.311
We would've had
a different result.

24:36.346 --> 24:36.902
Oh, come on.

24:36.937 --> 24:40.872
Why can't mr. Crane
take the drug and simply assume

24:40.907 --> 24:43.007
All the inherent risks
if he so chooses?

24:43.042 --> 24:44.583
Because we don't
let people take drugs

24:44.618 --> 24:46.854
While they're still
in the investigative stage,

24:46.889 --> 24:47.901
And with good reason.

24:47.936 --> 24:49.853
Think of
the potential for abuse.

24:49.888 --> 24:52.112
Potential for abuse?

24:52.147 --> 24:53.896
What's the downside?
He could die?

24:53.931 --> 24:55.207
He's doing that anyway.

24:55.208 --> 24:56.331
No, he isn't. He could live

24:56.332 --> 24:58.689
-A long time with alzheimer's.
-Which could be worse.

24:58.724 --> 25:00.914
And it's possible the disease
could take years to progress.

25:00.949 --> 25:02.828
He could have many
healthy years while we--

25:02.863 --> 25:05.882
There are all kinds
of possibilities and choices.

25:05.917 --> 25:08.825
Why can't they belong
to the patient?

25:08.860 --> 25:09.864
There is still so much

25:09.899 --> 25:11.935
That is still so unknown
about dimebolin that--

25:11.970 --> 25:13.681
Yes, and we'll assume
all of the risks.

25:13.682 --> 25:15.566
-Do i ever get to speak?
-I'd prefer you didn't.

25:15.601 --> 25:16.986
-We're wasting precious time.
-Mr. Shore,

25:17.144 --> 25:19.416
I  am a superior court judge.

25:19.451 --> 25:22.703
I have to take my cues
from the appellate court.

25:22.738 --> 25:24.990
On this issue,
the law is clear.

25:25.025 --> 25:28.314
A patient,
even a dying patient,

25:28.349 --> 25:31.576
Has no constitutional right
to experimental treatment.

25:31.611 --> 25:34.745
Now do i agree with that
precedent? No, not really.

25:34.780 --> 25:36.269
So this is what i will do--

25:36.664 --> 25:39.385
I'll certify it to the
massachusetts supreme court.

25:39.420 --> 25:41.076
Maybe they can find
the authority

25:41.111 --> 25:42.655
To give you what you want.

25:43.292 --> 25:44.903
We are adjourned.

25:49.944 --> 25:51.404
So now what?

25:52.340 --> 25:54.251
We go to
the state supreme court.

25:54.940 --> 25:55.752
There's nine of them.

25:55.787 --> 25:57.321
Let's hope that at least one
has a relative

25:57.356 --> 25:59.585
Who has an incurable disease.

26:09.924 --> 26:13.040
When was the last time
a pretty lady sat ne to you

26:13.075 --> 26:14.949
And sucked on your ear lobe?

26:15.369 --> 26:17.956
And don't count
the number of times

26:17.991 --> 26:20.104
You had to pay for it.

26:20.584 --> 26:21.996
How dare you?

26:22.031 --> 26:23.922
I'm eating my lunch.

26:23.957 --> 26:27.586
Oh, come on, sweetheart.
Throw an old lady a bone.

26:27.621 --> 26:29.464
You are....

26:29.499 --> 26:31.809
a shocking woman!

26:31.844 --> 26:35.623
Look, judge, i know
this is--Is ex parte

26:35.658 --> 26:37.359
Or some--Whatever, uh, uh,

26:37.394 --> 26:41.220
Some latin term that means
i can't gum your body parts.

26:41.255 --> 26:45.579
But why don't you just give me
something good to watch on tv?

26:45.614 --> 26:48.788
I mean, the airwaves are
a public trust. Am i right?

26:48.823 --> 26:50.475
Uh, catherine,
what are you doing?

26:50.510 --> 26:53.125
She's trying
to suck on my ear.

26:53.160 --> 26:54.404
That's what she's doing.

26:54.439 --> 26:56.341
-Outrageous!
-Catherine,

26:56.444 --> 26:57.494
Go inside the courthouse.

26:57.529 --> 26:59.925
I'll meet you there. Now.

27:08.544 --> 27:10.158
Ahem. I apologize, judge.

27:10.193 --> 27:11.286
You ask me,

27:11.321 --> 27:13.407
Your client already watches
too much television.

27:13.442 --> 27:15.893
-Ah.
-And that smutty mouth.

27:15.928 --> 27:17.947
Sex, sex, sex, sex.

27:17.982 --> 27:19.065
That what you watch?

27:19.100 --> 27:21.259
Silence!

27:21.294 --> 27:23.510
Uh, well,
you know, judge,

27:23.545 --> 27:26.187
In addition to there being
little for us to watch,

27:26.222 --> 27:28.451
Most of it stinks,

27:28.954 --> 27:30.882
And it's partly
this thing's fault.

27:30.917 --> 27:32.194
What are you talking about?

27:32.229 --> 27:34.433
Well, a lot of people are on it
while they're watching.

27:34.468 --> 27:37.179
They no longer give television
their undivided attention.

27:37.214 --> 27:38.259
We're either on the phone

27:38.294 --> 27:41.723
Or we're texting
or on the internet.

27:41.758 --> 27:44.394
So the producers,
they dumb down the plots,

27:44.429 --> 27:49.011
Make it easier to keep up with
while their viewers multitask.

27:49.046 --> 27:49.718
Really?

27:50.171 --> 27:53.471
Kids nowadays watch an average
of three hours of television a day.

27:53.506 --> 27:55.081
That's while being distracted.

27:55.116 --> 27:58.069
People over 55,
we watch 6 hours a day.

27:58.104 --> 28:00.655
And we really watch.

28:00.690 --> 28:02.750
So why aren't they
programming for us?

28:02.785 --> 28:05.151
You know, come on,
do these idiots a favor, judge.

28:05.449 --> 28:08.605
Send these network bozos
a clue. Be a leader.

28:08.785 --> 28:10.860
And we can't wait
for congress after all,

28:11.429 --> 28:14.591
Because, well,
they're bozos, too.

28:23.053 --> 28:25.863
These are their minds
they're messing with.

28:25.898 --> 28:28.215
We don't even know
the long-Term damage.

28:28.250 --> 28:29.104
Now obviously,

28:29.139 --> 28:32.014
Short of requiring
urinalysis at the s.A.T.S,

28:32.049 --> 28:34.565
We can't monitor who is
or isn't using,

28:34.600 --> 28:37.143
But we can take a stand
against the ones

28:37.178 --> 28:38.613
Who are brazen about it,

28:38.648 --> 28:41.685
Who defend it
as acceptable and fair.

28:41.720 --> 28:44.421
Simply put,
what margie coggins did

28:44.456 --> 28:46.379
Was decidedly unfair.

28:46.414 --> 28:48.171
It's cheating.

28:48.883 --> 28:51.726
Not in keeping with the ideals
of harvard.

28:52.889 --> 28:54.337
I got into harvard.

28:54.801 --> 28:56.081
Most don't.

28:56.116 --> 28:58.291
Harvard rejects
over 90% of its applicants.

28:58.326 --> 29:01.330
That's 90% of
the best high school students.

29:01.365 --> 29:04.609
The rest don't even
bother applying.

29:04.644 --> 29:05.840
The problem is,

29:05.875 --> 29:09.208
Every parent wants their kid
to go to harvard.

29:09.243 --> 29:11.949
Parents push, nudge.
Some kick.

29:12.128 --> 29:14.273
Look at the climate
we've created.

29:14.558 --> 29:16.385
80% of honors

29:16.420 --> 29:18.204
And advance-Placement
students cheat,

29:18.239 --> 29:21.682
Not once or twice,
but on a regular basis.

29:21.717 --> 29:23.004
She didn't.

29:23.005 --> 29:24.804
She didn't get
the test answers ahead of time.

29:24.839 --> 29:26.331
She didn't copy
her neighbor's paper.

29:26.366 --> 29:28.229
She used her own brain.

29:28.264 --> 29:32.508
Yes, she used a prescription stimulant
to stay focused and alert.

29:32.543 --> 29:36.659
At least 30% of college students
admit to doing the same thing.

29:36.694 --> 29:38.877
Not only are there currently
no laws against it,

29:38.912 --> 29:40.779
There are currently no rules.

29:40.814 --> 29:44.131
These kids grow up
in a pervasive drug culture.

29:44.166 --> 29:46.643
We've got medications
not just to treat diseases,

29:46.678 --> 29:48.726
But simply to help you
do things better,

29:48.761 --> 29:50.837
Be it sex, urinating, digesting.

29:50.872 --> 29:53.796
We've got some to boost energy,
others to help you sleep.

29:53.831 --> 29:54.707
Better life,

29:54.742 --> 29:57.495
More productive life
through chemistry.

29:58.873 --> 30:00.083
The drug
we're talking about here

30:00.118 --> 30:03.922
Is used off label by many
to boost brain power.

30:03.957 --> 30:05.548
Personally...

30:05.583 --> 30:09.683
i've tried medication
to help with my asperger's.

30:09.718 --> 30:11.218
Some worked.

30:11.253 --> 30:14.931
They made me
feel safer emotionally.

30:16.019 --> 30:17.794
Should i not get that right?

30:17.829 --> 30:22.269
Or are drugs for emotions okay,
but cognition, no?

30:22.304 --> 30:24.725
Or should the rule be
for disorder, yes,

30:24.760 --> 30:26.829
But enhancement, no?

30:26.864 --> 30:28.498
Where do you draw that line?

30:28.533 --> 30:30.844
She didn't have a prescription
for the ones she took.

30:30.879 --> 30:33.140
True, but many kids do this.
She's no different.

30:33.175 --> 30:35.207
-Except she got caught.
-She didn't get caught.

30:35.242 --> 30:36.854
She was simply honest about it.

30:36.889 --> 30:38.697
Honesty--That's the infraction

30:38.732 --> 30:41.400
That's getting her bounced
on moral character grounds.

30:41.435 --> 30:44.324
Hypocrisy might be
a better word.

31:21.095 --> 31:22.519
What are you doing?

31:23.798 --> 31:25.328
I'm giving the bride away,
remember?

31:25.363 --> 31:27.891
-Oh.
-I'm practicing.

31:30.556 --> 31:32.072
I want to get it right.

31:34.079 --> 31:36.086
